                                                                                                     super Keyword
super Keyword (Parent Class Reference)
Definition
↬ super refers to the immediate parent class object.
● It is used to access:
➱ Parent class variables
➱ Parent class methods
➱ Parent class constructors
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
1️⃣ Access Parent Class Variable
class A {
    int x = 10;   // Parent class variable
}

class B extends A {
    int x = 20;   // Child class variable

    void show() {
        System.out.println("Value of x from parent class (super.x): " + super.x);
        System.out.println("Value of x from child class (this.x): " + this.x);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        B obj = new B();
        obj.show();
    }
}
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
2️⃣ Call Parent Class Method
class Parent {
    void display() {
        System.out.println("Parent display");
    }
}

class Child extends Parent {
    void display() {
        super.display();
        System.out.println("Child display");
    }
}
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
3️⃣ Call Parent Class Constructor
class A {
    A() {
        System.out.println("Parent constructor");
    }
}

class B extends A {
    B() {
        super();   // implicit if not written
        System.out.println("Child constructor");
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new B();
    }
}

Output:
Parent constructor
Child constructor
⚠ Rule:
super() must be the first statement
If not written, Java calls it automatically
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
★ this vs super
| Feature          | this           | super         |
| ---------------- | -------------- | ------------- |
| Refers to        | Current object | Parent object |
| Access variable  | Yes            | Yes           |
| Call method      | Yes            | Yes           |
| Call constructor | Yes            | Yes           |
| Static allowed   | No             | No            |
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
★★ Key Interview Points
➢ this.x → refers to current class variable
➢ super.x → refers to parent class variable
➢ Used when same variable/method name exists in parent and child
➢ Helps avoid ambiguity in inheritance
